---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { site } from "../data/site";

const researchThreads = [
  {
    id: "measurement",
    title: "Measurement Before Modeling",
    body:
      "A lot of empirical work goes wrong before the model starts: the outcome, treatment, ideology score, response-quality flag, or institutional trait is made too casually. I work on measures for open-ended survey answers, legislative text, state capacity, public opinion, and other concepts that do not arrive as clean variables."
  },
  {
    id: "text",
    title: "Text as Institutional Evidence",
    body:
      "Text is a record of institutional action in my work. Bill sections, committee hearings, agency language, and country statements show what actors chose to say, delegate, hide, or emphasize. The point of the NLP is to recover something substantively meaningful from those choices."
  },
  {
    id: "design",
    title: "Design Under Real Constraints",
    body:
      "Policy and program evaluations rarely hand over clean assignment. I work on designs that make the identifying assumptions visible, especially when treatment timing, administrative records, and implementation quality are part of the problem."
  },
  {
    id: "public-opinion",
    title: "Public Opinion After Conversation",
    body:
      "The deliberation work is not only about whether survey marginals move for a weekend. The stronger test is whether people leave with different knowledge, reasoning, attention, and later political behavior."
  }
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title={`Research | ${site.name}`}
  description="Research on measurement, text, causal inference, institutions, and public opinion."
>
  <section class="panel span-12">
    <div class="eyebrow">Research</div>
    <h1>Research</h1>
    <p class="lede section-intro">
      Most of my work begins with a construct that people are willing to name but have not yet
      measured very well.
    </p>
    <p class="section-intro">
      That is the interesting part. If the construct were obvious and the data were clean, the
      methods would have less to prove.
    </p>
    <div class="anchor-row">
      {researchThreads.map((thread) => (
        <a class="anchor-link" href={`#${thread.id}`}>{thread.title}</a>
      ))}
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section-grid">
    {researchThreads.map((thread) => (
      <article class="panel span-6 theme-card" id={thread.id}>
        <div>
          <h2>{thread.title}</h2>
          <p>{thread.body}</p>
        </div>
      </article>
    ))}
  </section>

  <section class="section-grid">
    <div class="panel span-8">
      <h2>How I Use Methods</h2>
      <p>
        A method is not a credential. It is a bet that a particular simplification makes the
        evidence more honest.
      </p>
      <p>
        That is why the same site has papers on LLMs and legislative complexity, malpractice claims,
        state capacity, congressional agenda control, automated deliberation, and survey
        nonresponse. They look different from the outside. They share a worry about whether the
        quantity being analyzed is the quantity the argument needs.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="panel span-4">
      <h2>Where to Go Next</h2>
      <div class="compact-list">
        <div class="compact-item">
          <p><a href="/publications">Read abstracts and working papers</a></p>
        </div>
        <div class="compact-item">
          <p><a href="/talks">See recent talks and short courses</a></p>
        </div>
        <div class="compact-item">
          <p><a href="/cv">Download the current CV</a></p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
